    "narrative": "For our May 2nd slate, **Trevor Story** (75.93) and **Tyler Soderstrom** (68.54) stand out as our most potent offensive levers. **Trevor Story** benefits from a massive 19% SP skill boost against a favorable matchup, and crucially, the slow delivery of the opposing pitcher creates an ideal environment for our stolen base-heavy focus. Meanwhile, **Tyler Soderstrom** is primed for a high-efficiency outing, buoyed by a 10% park factor and a favorable platoon advantage against a mid-tier arm. **Vinnie Pasquantino** also warrants attention; despite some park headwinds, his 14% platoon boost and premium spot in the order result in a strong 67.84 score. We are also monitoring **Austin Riley**, whose 62.77 score is driven primarily by a robust park factor, though he remains a \"Lineup Pending\" risk until confirmed.\n\nOur most difficult decision occurred at the fringe of the bench, where **Jose Caballero** (41.62) narrowly missed the final cut. While **Jose Caballero** remains our primary weapon for stolen base production, he was victimized by a difficult matchup against a high-skill pitcher and a suppressed batting order position, making him a statistically inferior play compared to the likes of **Travis Bazzana**, whose elite 0.408 xwOBA profile keeps him in the lineup despite a sub-optimal platoon split. We are exercising caution with **Mickey Moniak**, whose score is suppressed by a brutal matchup against Chris Sale and a disadvantageous platoon split; he remains a start only because our internal thresholds favor his remaining volume over the marginal upside of **Alex Freeland** or **Kyle Karros**. We remain on high alert for weather risks and final lineup confirmations, as the volatility of these \"Lineup Pending\" designations for **Luis Campusano** and **Dalton Rushing** could force late-inning adjustments to our roster configuration.",
